
# __Unit 7 | Assignment - Distinguishing Sentiments__

 > ## **Observations**
 
> 1. From the overall media sentiment based on its past 100 tweets, BBC is most positive at 9.9% and NYTimes is the second    most positive with 3.9%. FoxNews bring up the final positive overall sentiment with 3.2%
> 2. Throughout working with this project, there was high volatility of the overall media sentiment depending on the day,    as certain days have more negative tweets, and other days all media might be positive across the board. I did a much lower      overall percentage of positive tweets than in the past on other github users in the past year.
> 3. The results also show that CNN is most negative with -6.7% negative polarity and CBSNews is second with -3.9%.


```python
import numpy as np
import seaborn as sns
from matplotlib import pyplot as plt
import pandas as pd
import tweepy
from datetime import datetime
import time
import json

np.random.seed()

# Import and Initialize Sentiment Analyzer
from vaderSentiment.vaderSentiment import SentimentIntensityAnalyzer
analyzer = SentimentIntensityAnalyzer()

# Twitter API Keys
from config import (consumer_key, 
                    consumer_secret, 
                    access_token, 
                    access_token_secret)

# Setup Tweepy API Authentication
auth = tweepy.OAuthHandler(consumer_key, consumer_secret)
auth.set_access_token(access_token, access_token_secret)
api = tweepy.API(auth, parser=tweepy.parsers.JSONParser())
```

##  __Twitter API Keys__


```python
# Twitter API Keys
consumer_key = consumer_key
consumer_secret = consumer_secret
access_token = access_token
access_token_secret = access_token_secret
```

##  __News Sources Defined__


```python
# Target Term
news_source = ["BBC", "CBSNews", "CNN", "FoxNews", "nytimes"] 
```


```python
# Set variables
sentiments_all = []
counter = 1
```

##  __Loop Through News Data__


```python
# Loop thru news sources for the most rescent 100 tweets
for news in news_source:
    # Creat loop to loop thru 5 pages of tweets (20 tweets per page)
    for x in range(5):
        compound_list = []
        negative_list = []
        positive_list = []
        neutral_list = []
        
        tweets = api.user_timeline(news, page=x)
        #loop thru tweets and parse data
        for tweet in tweets:
#             # Append tweet response
#             tweet_scource.append(tweet["user"]["name"])
#             tweet_text.append(tweet["text"])
#             tweet_date.append(tweet["created_at"])
            
            # Run Vader Analysis on each tweet
            compound = analyzer.polarity_scores(tweet["text"])["compound"]
            pos = analyzer.polarity_scores(tweet["text"])["pos"]
            neu = analyzer.polarity_scores(tweet["text"])["neu"]
            neg = analyzer.polarity_scores(tweet["text"])["neg"]
            tweets_ago = counter

            # Add each value to the appropriate array
            compound_list.append(compound)
            positive_list.append(pos)
            negative_list.append(neg)
            neutral_list.append(neu)
            
            
# Add sentiments for each tweet into an array
            sentiments_all.append({"News": news, 
                                   "Source account": tweet["source"],
                                   "Date": tweet["created_at"],        
                                   "Text": tweet["text"],
                                   "Compound": compound,
                                   "Positive": pos,
                                   "Negative": neu,
                                   "Neutral": neg,
                                   "Tweets Ago": counter
            })
    
            counter = counter + 1
```

##  __Set Dataframe from New Dictionary__


```python
# Convert sentiments to DataFrame
sentiments_pd = pd.DataFrame.from_dict(sentiments_all)
sentiments_pd
```

>  __Set Data For 100 Latest Tweets__


```python
# Plot all 5 News Media latest 100 tweets on one scatter plot

%matplotlib notebook

fig = plt.figure()
ax = fig.add_subplot(111)
ax.set_facecolor('lavender')
BBC = ax.scatter(np.arange(len(compound_df["BBC Compound"])),
         compound_df["BBC Compound"], marker="o", color="turquoise", edgecolors="k",
         alpha=0.8, s=80 ) 
CBSNews = ax.scatter(np.arange(len(compound_df["CBSNews Compound"])),
         compound_df["CBSNews Compound"], marker="o", color="green", edgecolors="k",
         alpha=0.8,s=80)
CNN = ax.scatter(np.arange(len(compound_df["CNN Compound"])),
         compound_df["CNN Compound"], marker="o", color="red", edgecolors="k",
         alpha=0.8 ,s=80)
FoxNews = ax.scatter(np.arange(len(compound_df["FoxNews Compound"])),
         compound_df["FoxNews Compound"], marker="o", color="blue", edgecolors="k",
         alpha=0.8,s=80)
nytimes = ax.scatter(np.arange(len(compound_df["NYtimes Compound"])),
         compound_df["NYtimes Compound"], marker="o", color="yellow", edgecolors="k",
         alpha=0.8,s=80)
# Modify ticks
plt.xlim(101,-1)
plt.ylim(-1, 1)
# setting labels
plt.title(f"Sentiment Analysis of Media Tweets (8/26/18)")
plt.xlabel("Tweets Ago")
plt.ylabel("Tweet Polarity")
plt.grid(True, linestyle='dashed')

#plt.legend(title='news_source', bbox_to_anchor=(0.95, 0.60))
plt.legend((BBC, CBSNews, CNN, FoxNews, nytimes), ("BBC", "CBSNews", "CNN", "FoxNews", "nytimes"),
           title="Media Source", 
           loc="lower left", 
           bbox_to_anchor=(1, 0.7))

# Savefig as tight so you can see the legend as png           
plt.savefig("Sentiment Analysis of Media Tweets", bbox_inches="tight")
plt.show()
```

## __Plot Overall Sentiment on a Bar Chart__


```python
# Get overall compound sentiment of all 5 news outlets
average_sentiment = sentiments_pd.groupby("News")["Compound"].mean()
average_sentiment
```




    News
    BBC        0.099225
    CBSNews   -0.039457
    CNN       -0.067009
    FoxNews    0.032160
    nytimes    0.039991
    Name: Compound, dtype: float64




```python
# # Set the aesthetic using Seaborn
sns.set()

fig = plt.figure()
ax = fig.add_subplot(111)
x_axis = np.arange(len(average_sentiment))
xlabels = average_sentiment.index
count = 0
for sentiment in average_sentiment:
    plt.text(count, sentiment+.01, str(round(sentiment,2)))
    count = count + 1
plt.bar(x_axis, average_sentiment, tick_label = xlabels, color = ['turquoise', 'green', 'red', 'blue', 'yellow'])
ax.set_ylabel('Tweet Polarity')
ax.set_title("Overrall Media Sentiment based on Twitter (8/26/2018)")
ax.set_facecolor('lavender')
# plt.xticks(tick_locations, Compound_mean_df["News"])
plt.axhline(0, color='k')

# Save fig as png
plt.savefig("Overrall_Media_Sentiment_8_26_2018")
plt.show()
```
